<subSubSection pageId="37" pageNumber="166" type="conservation">
<paragraph blockId="37.[167,1374,1287,2421]" pageId="37" pageNumber="166">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[169,521,2036,2065]" pageId="37" pageNumber="166">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List. The Orinoco Four-eyed Opossum occurs in an area of extensive, suitable habitat that does not appear to be under threat, and presumably it has a large overall population. It occurs in several protected areas: Guarapiche Forest Reserve, Delta del Orinoco (Mariusa) National Park, and Delta del Orinoco Biosphere Reserve. The vast majority of the known distribution of the Orinoco Four-eyed Opossum is uninhabited by humans. The area does not have extensive human settlements, but there have been surveys for oil in the area, and there are plans to drill for oil and build gas pipes, which could represent future conservation threats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
